{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h3><a href=\"https://itp.nyu.edu/physcomp/labs/labs-arduino-digital-and-analog/digital-input-and-output-with-an-arduino/\">Lab 2</a> documentation</h3>\n<p>A simple circuit to flip the state of two LEDs when a pushbutton is pressed. One of the LEDs is on by default (before interaction), while the other one is off.</p>\n<iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/291971060\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>\n<p>This circuit uses a 10M ohm pulldown resistor (sorry, forgot to label on the diagram) connected to the pushbutton switch and two 150 ohm resistors for the LEDs.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/week-3-pushbutton-1-ed8e57b707871ed2b52df047d7cd35b1-5ea44.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 768px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 133.33333333333331%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"pushbutton-1\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/week-3-pushbutton-1-ed8e57b707871ed2b52df047d7cd35b1-5ea44.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/week-3-pushbutton-1-ed8e57b707871ed2b52df047d7cd35b1-e0edb.jpg 222w,\n/static/week-3-pushbutton-1-ed8e57b707871ed2b52df047d7cd35b1-b04ee.jpg 444w,\n/static/week-3-pushbutton-1-ed8e57b707871ed2b52df047d7cd35b1-5ea44.jpg 768w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/week-3-pushbutton-2-f0ff59b5cc999c05b8b36e2e1bfd0a84-5ea44.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 768px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 133.33333333333331%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"pushbutton-2\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/week-3-pushbutton-2-f0ff59b5cc999c05b8b36e2e1bfd0a84-5ea44.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/week-3-pushbutton-2-f0ff59b5cc999c05b8b36e2e1bfd0a84-e0edb.jpg 222w,\n/static/week-3-pushbutton-2-f0ff59b5cc999c05b8b36e2e1bfd0a84-b04ee.jpg 444w,\n/static/week-3-pushbutton-2-f0ff59b5cc999c05b8b36e2e1bfd0a84-5ea44.jpg 768w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h3>Code</h3>\n<pre><code class=\"language-c\">void setup() {\n  pinMode(2, INPUT);\n  pinMode(3, OUTPUT);\n  pinMode(4, OUTPUT);\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n  if (digitalRead(2) == HIGH) {\n    digitalWrite(3, HIGH);\n    digitalWrite(4, LOW);\n  } else {\n    digitalWrite(3, LOW);\n    digitalWrite(4, HIGH);\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>","frontmatter":{"date":"25 September 2018","title":"Week 3 - Lab 2 - Digital Input and Output with an Arduino"},"fields":{"category":"physical-computing","slug":"/blog/itp/physical-computing/week-3-lab-2/"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/blog/itp/physical-computing/week-3-lab-2/"}}